prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Observing mode and correlator setup: This is a continuum observation in Band 7.
Angular resolution: Our aim is to observe the global dust content of the targets. The galaxies have an extent <1". We therefore request an angular resolution of 1".
Sensitivity and time estimate: Our aim is to reach a noise rms of 0.1 mJy for each target. This will allow a 5sigma detection of the (conservatively) estimated dust mass. The OT Sensitivity Calculator gives a total observing time of 3.0 hours, including calibrations and overheads. A minor time saving can be achieved as two sources are within 8.2" from each other and can be covered in a single pointing.
Dynamic range: This is a detection experiment and we do not have any requests for the image fidelity.
Data rate and time constraints are no issues for this proposal.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
Two fundamental questions regarding the formation and evolution of galaxies are how they acquire their gas content and how this is turned into stars. Observations at restframe optical wavelengths suggest that the gas accretion rate exceeds the star formation rate at z>4, and the baryonic content is dominated by the interstellar gas. We currently have little observational data on the evolution of the gas and the star formation history of galaxies at z>3. It is therefore of vital importance to establish the gas fraction in galaxies as a function of redshift. This is a difficult undertaking, but with ALMA it is, for the first time, possible to do this in a systematic way. Currently it is not possible to undertake such a survey using CO or [CII] lines.
We propose to observe a sample of galaxies at z~3, 4 and 5, using the optically thin dust continuum as a proxy for the interstellar gas. The sample is selected as the 20 top ranking galaxies in terms of stellar mass in each redshift bin. This selection is similar to selecting galaxies at a constant number density and allows a direct comparison the evolution of related galaxies across cosmic time.
